range in the UK. In conclusion, the available pharmacoeconomic data indicate 
that rufinamide is more effective, but more expensive, than alternative 
adjunctive therapies approved for use in patients with LGS in the UK. Rufinamide 
would appear to be a cost-effective alternative to topiramate. Although 
rufinamide exceeds conventional cost-effectiveness thresholds when compared with 
lamotrigine, it may still be considered a valuable treatment option for a 
devastating orphan disease such as LGS.

