642. Gerontology. 2012;58(4):331-6. doi: 10.1159/000334242. Epub 2012 Feb 16.

Prostate-specific antigen screening for prostate cancer in older men in the 
United States of America.

Black A(1), Berg CD.

Author information:
(1)Division of Cancer Epidemiology and Genetics, National Cancer Institute, 
Rockville, MD 20852, USA.

Prostate cancer, like many diseases, is more common in older men. Although an 
estimated 1 in 7 men will be diagnosed with it, the majority of these men will 
not die from prostate cancer. The latent nature of this disease, the use of 
screening with prostate-specific antigen (PSA) testing and the greater risk of 
dying from causes other than prostate cancer contribute to this disparity. As 
the US population continues to age, prostate cancer screening and disease 
management presents an increasingly important public health issue. We discuss 
the current PSA screening recommendations and practices in the USA and the 
benefits and harms of screening older populations.

